DESCRIPTION: This item funds modifications to C/KC-130 aircraft. The Lockheed C/KC-130 aircraft is a four engine, high-wing, all metal, long range, land based monoplane capable of all-weather transport of cargo or personnel and in-flight refueling. There are currently 96 aircraft in the Navy and Marine Corps inventory (53 active and 43 reserve). The expected Service Life is as follows:

T/M/S Service Date Service Life Expected Life
C-130T      10/91 - 11/95 450 mos.         2028-2032
KC-130T     04/84 - 02/96 450 mos.         2021-2033
KC-130J     09/00 - 10/26 450 mos.         2037-2063

Justification.val: Basis for FY2020 Budget request:  Provides funding to procure aircraft modifications to include Weapons Mission Kits, Electronic Countermeasures, Safety, Reliability, Readiness and Obsolescence Issues and Communication Navigation Surveillance System (CNS) Air Traffic Management (ATM) requirements such as Block Upgrade 8.1, and Avionics Obsolescence Upgrade (AOU) for the C/KC-130 program.

Description.val:
DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION: The KC-130 provides air-to-air refueling (AAR), aviation delivered ground refueling, tactical troop transport, aerial delivery of personnel and cargo, airborne radio relay, Digital Interoperability (DI), tactical aero-medical evacuation, Multi-Sensor Imagery and Reconnaissance (MIR), and Close Air Support (CAS).  The objective of this effort is to integrate an MIR and air-to-ground weapons systems kit into the KC-130J aircraft to provide the Marine Air-Ground Task Force (MAGTF) with an intra-theater CAS and MIR capability for real time intelligence gathering and target detection, identification, and tracking in support of weapons delivery.  The MIR/Weapon System Kit will consist of a MIR pod, and wing mounted air-to-ground missiles and precision guided munitions. The system will be configured as a Roll-On/Roll-Off capability for rapid deployment.  Future capabilities will  support DI and include video and datalink connectivity, Beyond Line of Sight (BLOS) communications, Hellfire P4/N4 compatibility, recovery of external fuel stores, and dual AAR systems, improved human factors, Joint Air to Ground Munitions (JAGM), small diameter bombs, and address obsolescence, test platform, and capability gaps.

DEVELOPMENT STATUS/MAJOR DEVELOPMENT MILESTONES:  The KC-130J MIR/Weapons Mission Kit configuration provides MIR Weapon System Capability and CAS capability through both wing mounted munitions and Derringer Door mounted Standoff Precision Guided Munitions. The 6 baseline MIR/Weapons Mission Kits and 10 baseline aircraft modifications completed production in FY14. This Operational, Safety, and Improvement Program (OSIP) provides funding to address obsolescence issues [update Battle Management System (BMS) for Hellfire P4/N4 variant missiles] and JAGM, human factors issues, and fleet capability gaps (recover external fuel stores, recover dual AAR systems, tactical datalink gap, and communications gap). A-Kits and B-Kits in FY18-FY24 address fleet capability gaps.

Name.@footnote: Increase in FY20 data correlates with the completion of NRE/Test efforts.
Other support includes lead systems integrator cost to develop and deliver AOU modification kits.

Description.val:
DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION: Objective of the Avionics/Obsolescence Upgrades (AOU) Operational, Safety, and Improvement Program (OSIP) is to preserve the world-wide capabilities of the C/KC-130 aircraft by providing required capability  enhancements and addressing obsolescence. The legacy C/KC-130T model aircraft have been in service for 27 years and still retain many of their original systems. AOU incorporates updated technologies to support safety, reliability, supportability, obsolescence, deficiency correction, mandated modifications, commonality, interoperability, and affordability of the C/KC-130T platform.  AOU updates apply to aircraft avionics, navigation, communications, transponders, sensors, transmitters, antennae, radars, and other electronic aircraft systems to meet global Communication, Navigation, and Surveillance/Air Traffic Management (CNS/ATM) requirements and provides necessary safety equipment for aircraft carrying troops.  AOU modifications will also be incorporated into existing training devices.  


DEVELOPMENT STATUS/MAJOR DEVELOPMENT MILESTONES:  AOU program is post Milestone-C, Low Rate Initial Production 2  approved. Government is Lead Systems Integrator, performing the majority of the NRE and installation of the validation and verification aircraft kits. Contract awarded for software integration non-recurring engineering and non-developmental systems in September 2012. Government ground testing on validation aircraft began 2017. Development Flight Test began January 2019 following a 14 month delay due to the K/C-130T Red Stripe that grounded most of the C/KC-130T fleet in September 2017. Validation aircraft will complete testing in FY20. Verification aircraft will undergo installation through 2020, followed by production installs.

Description.val:
DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION:  The KC-130 provides air-to-air refueling, rapid ground refueling, tactical troop transport, aerial delivery of personnel and cargo, airborne radio relay, Digital Interoperability (DI), tactical aero-medical evacuation, Multi-Sensor Imagery and Reconnaissance (MIR), and Close Air Support (CAS). This OSIP provides funding for the addition of new Aircraft Survivability Equipment (ASE), including Department of the Navy (DoN) Large Aircraft Infrared Counter Measures (LAIRCM) with Advanced Threat Warning (ATW) and the KC-130J Adjustable Ballast System (JABS) to the KC-130J Aircraft which will increase survivability and allow the aircraft to operate under expanded threat environments, thereby increasing combat effectiveness. The addition of DoN LAIRCM with the ATW sensor expands the aircraft's capability to perform its core Mission Essential Tasking in any infrared threat environment.  This OSIP also provides funding to ensure the most effective threat adaptive, reprogrammable, computer controlled threat defeating capabilities for the Defensive Electronic Counter Measures (DECM) portion of the ASE to increase combat effectiveness as well as future upgrades to the radar warning receiver (RWR) counter measure system.


DEVELOPMENT STATUS/MAJOR DEVELOPMENT MILESTONES:  The USMC is leveraging other DoN LAIRCM platforms to provide a common solution among naval platforms and to reduce Operations and Support (O&S) costs.  Modification of aircraft will be performed as a Drive-In Modification.

Description.val:
DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION: Technical Insertion provides for the incorporation and/or Tactical Demonstration (TACDEMO) of new or updated technologies to support safety, reliability, supportability, obsolescence, deficiency correction, mandated modifications, commonality, Digital Interoperability (DI), Electronic Warfare (EW), interoperability, C/KC-130 unique mission planning requirements, or affordability of the C/KC-130 platform.  Technical Insertion updates support those technology initiatives that apply to aircraft avionics, navigation, communications,transponders, sensors, transmitters, antennae, mission computers and associated systems, electronic mission systems, C/KC-130 unique mission planning requirements or other electronic aircraft systems.  

Current modifications include: KC-130J Block Upgrade 8.1, which includes Communication Navigation Surveillance System (CNS) Air Traffic Management (ATM) mandates, new Flight Management System (FMS), transponder and Mission Computer updates for Required Navigation Performance (RNP) and Area Navigation (RNAV) and Automatic Dependent Surveillance - Broadcast (ADS-B) Out, safety improvements Improved Intercom System (ICS) Portable Audio (PA) System and enhanced covert lighting, deficiency correction Telecommunications Electronics Material Protected from Emanating Spurious Transmissions (TEMPEST) compliance, and DI updates (Mode 5 Identification Friend and Foe (IFF) and Link 16). Unique C/KC-130 mission planning requirement CAT 5.0 and Flight Performance Model (FPM) Take-off and Landing Data (TOLD) certification. 

Planned future modifications: Capability Management Upgrade (CMU) with Flight Management System (FMS) performance enhancements to ensure future mission readiness of the KC-130J fleet, Software Reprogrammable Payload (SRP), the Blue Force Tracker (BFT), Blue Force Situational Awareness (BFSA) initiative, and Ku Band Satellite System (Kuss) Beyond Line of Sight (BLOS) to support DI within the Marine Air Ground Task Force (MAGTF) and across the services. Unique C/KC-130 mission planning requirements including map and communication tools. Development of tablet enabled applications such as Electronic Take-off and Landing Data (ETOLD), Weight and Balance (W&B), and FPM planning.

DEVELOPMENT STATUS/MAJOR DEVELOPMENT MILESTONES: Block 8.1 upgrade consists of 59 kits and installs starting in FY17 and completing beyond the FYDP.

Description.val:
DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION: This line item funds modifications to Navy C/KC-130 aircraft. To ensure preservation of Marine Air Ground Task Force (MAGTF) Assault Support and Navy-Unique Fleet Essential Aircraft capabilities world-wide, this Safety, Reliability, Readiness and Obsolescence Improvement OSIP provides funding for issues that adversely affect aircraft safety, reliability and/or availability. Applicable areas include Power and Propulsion, Airframes and Structures, Safety and Life Support, Electrical Power, Readiness Initiatives and Survivability.  This OSIP provides resources to correct such issues via Engineering Change Proposal (ECP) and other applicable efforts by modifying, improving, and upgrading aircraft structural safety and reliability.  Modifications include:  Airframe Structural Upgrades such as Flight Controls Surfaces, Forward Fuselage, Aft Fuselage, Inner/Outer Wing, Critical Structures; and Aircraft Subsystem Upgrades, such as Electrical, Hydraulic, Environmental Control Systems (ECS), Fuel, Launch and Recovery, Critical Structures, Mechanical, Secondary Power, and Fire Suppression Systems.

DEVELOPMENT STATUS/MAJOR DEVELOPMENT MILESTONES:  The current KC-130 aircraft do not have crashworthy observer seats in the cargo compartment required for safe operations in the tactical environment. The observer seats will provide increased crash attenuation, mission endurance, and restraint systems. The observer seats are Commercial Off The Shelf (COTS) items and are currently being installed in USAF C-130 Aircraft. Planned material solution is being updated to better meet USMC requirements. Current Inter-Communication System (ICS) system is a hardwire solution that impedes the aircrews' ability to carry out critical mission sets. A wireless ICS system will provide safer, unrestricted mobility for crew members to perform critical missions such as Aerial Cargo Delivery, ground and in-flight refueling. In addition, a wireless ICS facilitates crew members egress in the event of an emergency. The legacy 3,600 gallon fuel tanks in the cargo compartment need to be modified to fit the KC-130J due to obsolete components that are not compatible with the new KC-130J. Planned Engineering Change Proposals (ECP) for reliability are carbon brakes, corrosion control, and engine upgrades. Additionally, night vision goggles are being upgraded to white phosphorous as a safety improvement to the degraded visual environment.

Description.val:
DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION: The NP2000 is an eight bladed propeller system that uses a modular hydraulic control system similar to the existing 54H60-111 propeller. The propeller blades are composite. The NP2000 uses existing Electronic Propeller Control System (EPCS) components with slight modifications required.  The purpose of this modification is to support rapidly returning the C/KC-130T fleet to service and addressing the top readiness degrader for the legacy C/KC-130T aircraft. As a result of the C/KC-130T Red Stripe, the limited availability of 54H60-111 propellers has grounded most of the C/KC-130T fleet since Sep 2017. Modifying C/KC-130T aircraft with NP2000 reduces the demand on available 54H60-111 propellers and increases readiness of the Navy C-130 fleet.

DEVELOPMENT MILESTONES/MAJOR DEVELOPMENTAL MILESTONES: The NP2000 Modification is a Congressional Add program. The program is leveraging an existing propeller solution and the integration and testing performed by the USAF to integrate NP2000 into their fleet. NP2000 is a Turnkey effort that is contracted through NATO.  The prototype and validation aircraft were rapidly modified and delivered to the Fleet in September 2018. Installations will continue through FY20.
